  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="KT271-kilavi">talaimakaṉ vāyil nērntu pukka tōḻikkut talaimakaḷ colliyatu. </p>
        <p xml:lang="en">Uttered by HER to the confidante when HE entered after
          having been granted the door/mediation. </p>
      </div>

      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="KT271">
          <l> aruvi yaṉṉa paruvuṟai citaṟi</l>
          <l> yāṟuniṟai pakaru nāṭaṉait tēṟi</l>
          <l> yuṟṟatu maṉṉu morunāṇ maṟṟatu</l>
          <l> tavappaṉ ṉāṭōṇ mayaṅki</l>
          <l> vauvum paṇpi ṉōyā kiṉṟē.</l>
        </lg>

        <lg xml:lang="en">
          <l>Believing the man from the land where the river voices [its] fullness</l>
          <l rend="indent2">[and] scatters big drops like a waterfall,</l>
          <l>it happened, in fact. <note place="foot">
              <term xml:lang="ta">uṟṟatu maṉṉum</term> : What can be the function of -um here?
            Adding an additional reason (while the first one has not been uttered): "it indeed
            happened also ..."?</note>
          </l>
          <l rend="indent7">One day only [was] that.</l>
          <l>Very many days [my] shoulders <note place="foot">Here is another passage where <term xml:lang="ta">tōḷ</term> is obviously used in a metonymic-metaphorical way to denote
            HER body as having been touched by a man.</note> have been confused</l>
          <l><choice>
              <seg>[and that] of a nature which attracts <note place="foot">
                  <term xml:lang="ta">vauvum paṇpiṉ </term> can either be read as a qualification of
            an elliptical subject or as an attribute to <term xml:lang="ta">nōy</term> (see 5b).</note>
            became pain.</seg>
              <seg>[and] it became pain of the gripping kind.</seg>
            </choice></l>

          <lg type="alternate">
            <l> Believing the man from the land where the river voices [its] fullness</l>
            <l rend="indent2"> [and] scatters big drops like a waterfall,</l>
            <l> it happened, in fact, one day.</l>
            <l rend="indent7"> But that [same thing],</l>
            <l rend="indent2"> after distressing [my] shoulders for many days,</l>
            <l> became a pain of a nature that devours. <note place="foot">Thus the sentence
              splitting by Cām./T.V.G. – in order to be able to decide between the two it would be
              necessary to study in full the usage of the particle <term xml:lang="ta">maṟṟu</term>
              .</note>
            </l>
          </lg>

        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
